</style></head><body><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s1" style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 21pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">Programming Abstractions – Homework II</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 21pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.ritwikbanerjee.com/" class="s2" target="_blank">Dr. Ritwik Banerjee</a></p><p class="s3" style="padding-left: 21pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">Computer Science, Stony Brook University</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">In this assignment, you will be using Java (make sure it is JDK 1.8 compliant) for programming. Moreover, this assignment requires you to invest quite a bit into thinking about abstraction <span class="s4">before </span>you start coding. It is based on a mathematical structure called <b>group</b>. Before we get to the code, let us define this concept:</p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 91%;text-align: justify;">A nonempty set of elements <span class="s4">G </span>forms a <b>group </b>if in <span class="s4">G </span>there is a defined binary operation (which we will denote by <span class="s5">· </span>in this document), such that</p><ol id="l1"><li data-list-text="1."><p class="s4" style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 30pt;text-indent: -12pt;line-height: 15pt;text-align: justify;">x, y <span class="s5">∈ </span>G <span class="p">implies that </span>x <span class="s5">· </span>y <span class="s5">∈ </span>G<span class="p">. This property is called </span>closure<span class="p">, and the set of elements is said to be</span></p><p class="s4" style="padding-left: 30pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 10pt;text-align: left;">closed under the operation<span class="p">.</span></p></li><li data-list-text="2."><p class="s4" style="padding-left: 30pt;text-indent: -12pt;line-height: 13pt;text-align: left;">a, b, c <span class="s5">∈ </span>G <span class="p">implies that </span>a <span class="s5">· </span><span class="p">(</span>b <span class="s5">· </span>c<span class="p">) = (</span>a <span class="s5">· </span>b<span class="p">) </span><span class="s5">· </span>c<span class="p">. In other words, the binary operation is associative.</span></p></li><li data-list-text="3."><p class="s4" style="padding-left: 30pt;text-indent: -12pt;line-height: 13pt;text-align: left;"><span class="p">There exists an element </span>e <span class="s5">∈ </span>G <span class="p">such that </span>a <span class="s5">· </span>e <span class="p">= </span>e <span class="s5">· </span>a <span class="p">= </span>a <span class="p">for all elements </span>a <span class="s5">∈ </span>G<span class="p">. This special element </span>e</p><p style="padding-left: 30pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 10pt;text-align: left;">is called the <span class="s4">identity </span>element of the group.</p></li><li data-list-text="4."><p class="s4" style="padding-left: 30pt;text-indent: -12pt;line-height: 14pt;text-align: left;"><span class="p">For every </span>a <span class="s5">∈ </span>G<span class="p">, there exists an element </span>b <span class="p">such that </span>a <span class="s5">· </span>b <span class="p">= </span>b <span class="s5">· </span>a <span class="p">= </span>e<span class="p">. That is, every element has an</span></p></li></ol><p class="s4" style="padding-left: 30pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">inverse<span class="p">. Often, we simply denote it by </span>a<span class="s6">−</span><span class="s7">1</span><span class="p">.</span></p><p style="padding-top: 7pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Much like programming, mathematics also relies on abstraction. Groups have become fundamentally important in modern mathematics because they distill the basic structural rules found in almost every important mathematical structure. Some are very obvious, such as the set of all integers with addition as the binary operation. Note that the same set is NOT a group with multiplication as the operation (no inverse)! However, as soon as we consider a bigger set, namely, the set of all real numbers, even with multiplication we have a valid group. These examples serve to show that you should not simply think about the set of elements, but</p><p class="s4" style="padding-top: 1pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 91%;text-align: justify;"><span class="p">instead, carefully consider the binary operation together with the set. It is also important to note that the binary operation may not always be commutative. That is, it is not always the case that </span>a <span class="s5">· </span>b <span class="p">= </span>b <span class="s5">· </span>a<span class="p">.</span></p><p style="padding-left: 287pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 1pt;text-align: left;"/><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">For a basic understanding of implementing simple groups, there is some Java code already given to you. The most important is the interface called <span class="s8">Group</span>. It is extensively documented, and students are expected to pay attention to the details provided there. Next, there is an implementation of the most obvious group we can think of: the group of all integers under addition. This is provided to you as <a href="#bookmark0" style=" color: black; font-family:Cambria, serif; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none; font-size: 10pt;">ZPlus</a><span style=" color: #F00; font-family:&quot;Georgia Pro&quot;, serif; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none; font-size: 6.5pt; vertical-align: 3pt;">1</span>.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h1 style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Finite groups</h1><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Based on everything you have seen up to this point, you may think that groups are just a fancy way of stating the basic properties of numbers. But that is not at all true! To start with, a group need not be infinite. In fact, you will now be implementing a few finite groups.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h1 style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Non-commutative groups</h1><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s4" style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 82%;text-align: justify;"><span class="p">As noted earlier, the binary operation of a group need not be commutative. That is, </span>a <span class="s5">· </span>b <span class="p">is not always equal to </span>b <span class="s5">· </span>a<span class="p">. This may not be intuitive if you only think of numeric operations. But they make a lot of sense when we enter the world of geometry. In fact, one of the biggest applications of </span>group theory <span class="p">is in fields</span></p><p style="padding-top: 1pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">like chemistry and physics, where the structural symmetry of molecules and particles is studied using this mathematical concept. So much so, that many consider the study of groups to be the “science of symmetry”.</p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-bottom: 3pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">For this assignment, we will look at two very simple examples – an equilateral triangle and a square – and their symmetries.</p><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 1pt;text-align: left;"/><p class="s11" style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 11pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark0"><span class="s10">1</span></a>The name may seem strange, but <span class="s12">Z </span>is the standard mathematical symbol to represent the set of integers. And since addition is the binary operation for this group, I decided to call the class <span class="s13">ZPlus</span>.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">1</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark1">Figure 1: The eight symmetries of a square: the identity operation that leaves everything as it is, three rotation operations (around its center by 90</a><span class="s6">◦</span>, 180<span class="s6">◦</span>, and 270<span class="s6">◦</span>), two reflections around the horizontal and vertical lines, and two reflections around the two diagonals.</p><p style="padding-left: 51pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><span><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><img width="497" height="138" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"/></td></tr><tr><td><img width="497" height="138" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"/></td></tr></table></span></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">But first, another definition: two shapes are said to be <b>congruent</b>, if they have the same shape and size. Formally, two shapes are congruent if one can be changed into the other by using a combination of:</p><ol id="l2"><li data-list-text="(i)"><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 30pt;text-indent: -21pt;text-align: left;">rotations (around a fixed point),</p></li><li data-list-text="(ii)"><p style="padding-left: 30pt;text-indent: -21pt;text-align: left;">reflections (around a line that serves as the axis of the reflection), and/or</p></li><li data-list-text="(iii)"><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 3pt;line-height: 112%;text-align: left;">translations (a transformation that moves every point in the same direction by the same distance). Clearly, any shape in the 2-dimensional <span class="s4">x</span>-<span class="s4">y </span>plane is congruent to itself. Some shapes, however, are congruent to themselves in more than one way! Any such “extra” congruence is called a <b>symmetry</b>. A square has</p><p class="s16" style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;"><a href="#bookmark1" style=" color: black; font-family:Georgia, serif; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none; font-size: 10pt;">eight symmetries, as shown in Fig. </a>1<span style=" color: #000;">. Similarly, an equilateral triangle has six symmetries (three rotations</span></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 122%;text-align: left;">around its center by 0<span class="s6">◦</span>, 120<span class="s6">◦</span>, and 240<span class="s6">◦</span>, and three reflections around the three perpendicular bisectors). With this background, we are now ready to dive into some actual programming.</p><ol id="l3"><li data-list-text="1."><p style="padding-top: 7pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: -12pt;line-height: 86%;text-align: justify;">Let <span class="s4">G </span>be the set <span class="s5">{±</span>1<span class="s5">}</span>, under the standard multiplication of real numbers. Your first task is to implement this group in Java, with the name <span class="s8">FiniteGroupOfOrderTwo</span>.</p><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 81%;text-align: justify;">When thinking about implementing this, note that <span class="s8">Group </span>is a parameterized interface. In the implemented example, <span class="s8">ZPlus</span>, the parameter was obvious, because we already know the data type for “integers” (<span class="s8">Integer</span>, of course). But here, the valid data that forms the set of elements, consists of only two values. So think about what should be the data type of the generic parameter. In your implementation, this parameter class must be named <span class="s8">PlusOrMinusOne</span>. You should also ensure that the following driver method (given to you in the <span class="s8">ArithmeticTest </span>class) works with your code:</p><p class="s13" style="padding-top: 7pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">public static void main(String... args) {</p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 40pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">FiniteGroupOfOrderTwo g     = new FiniteGroupOfOrderTwo(); PlusOrMinusOne[]     values = PlusOrMinusOne.values(); System.out.printf(&quot;g.identity() = %s%n&quot;, g.identity());</p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 40pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">for (PlusOrMinusOne u : values) {</p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 74pt;text-indent: -16pt;text-align: left;">for (PlusOrMinusOne v : values) { PlusOrMinusOne e = g.binaryOperation(u, v);</p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 74pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">System.out.printf(&quot;%s * %s = %s%n&quot;, u.toString(), v.toString(), e.toString()); System.out.printf(&quot;inverseOf(%s) = %s%n&quot;, e.toString(), g.inverseOf(e).toString());</p><p style="padding-top: 8pt;padding-left: 10pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">(20)</p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 57pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">}</p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 40pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">}</p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">}</p><p style="padding-top: 7pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">In the above code, <span class="s8">toString() </span>must return only the numeric value (i.e., “1” or “-1”).</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s15" style="padding-left: 16pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><span><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><img width="261" height="262" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></td></tr></table></span>	<span><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><img width="265" height="267" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></td></tr></table></span></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark2">Figure 2: A radial graph, with one point as the central node. All other nodes are connected </a><span class="s4">only </span>to this center by a directed edge. All edges have the same length, and direct away from the center.</p><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark3">Figure 3: A geometric representation of an actual radial graph. Each point is a </a><span class="s8">Point </span>object, all the edges have the same length, and every edge direct away from the center.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li><li data-list-text="2."><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: -12pt;text-align: justify;">There is an interface called <span class="s8">Shape </span>provided in the <span class="s8">geometry </span>package. In this question, we will consider a <span class="s8">RadialGraph</span><a href="#bookmark2" style=" color: black; font-family:Georgia, serif; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none; font-size: 10pt;">, which is meant to represent objects of the type shown in Fig. </a><span style=" color: #F00;">2 </span><a href="#bookmark3" style=" color: black; font-family:Georgia, serif; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none; font-size: 10pt;">and Fig. </a><span style=" color: #F00;">3</span>. Such graphs show up all the time in social networks (<span class="s4">e.g.</span>, the central node represents an influencer with the others representing followers). Your task in this question is to complete the implementation of the <span class="s8">RadialGraph </span>class, consistent with the requirements of the <span class="s8">Shape </span>interface.</p><p style="padding-top: 4pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Most of the implementation is straight-forward. Implementing rotation (in the <span class="s8">rotateBy(int degrees)</span></p><p style="padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">method), however, requires some mathematics!</p><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Formally, rotation in the 2-dimensional Euclidean space is defined by a 2 <span class="s5">× </span>2 matrix. To rotate all the points in the <span class="s4">x</span>-<span class="s4">y </span>plane counterclockwise by an angle <span class="s4">θ </span>(in radians), with respect to the positive x axis about the origin, a point (<span class="s4">x, y</span>) is transformed by</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 10pt;text-align: left;">sin <span class="s4">θ  </span>cos <span class="s4">θ</span></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"/><p class="s4" style="text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 10pt;text-align: left;">y</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"/><p class="s4" style="text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 10pt;text-align: left;">x <span class="p">sin </span>θ <span class="p">+ </span>y <span class="p">cos </span>θ</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"/><p class="s4" style="padding-top: 7pt;padding-left: 21pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;"><span class="s17"> </span><span class="p">cos </span>θ  <span class="s5">− </span><span class="p">sin </span>θ<span class="s17">  </span>x<span class="s17"> </span><span class="s18">=</span><span class="s17"> </span>x <span class="p">cos </span>θ <span class="s5">− </span>y <span class="p">sin </span>θ<span class="s17"> </span></p><p class="s4" style="padding-top: 16pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 91%;text-align: justify;"><span class="p">Without the matrix notation used in linear algebra, this simply means that such a rotation transforms the point (</span>x, y<span class="p">) to the point (</span>x <span class="p">cos </span>θ <span class="s5">− </span>y <span class="p">sin </span>θ, x <span class="p">sin </span>θ <span class="p">+ </span>y <span class="p">cos </span>θ<a href="#bookmark4" style=" color: black; font-family:Georgia, serif; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none; font-size: 10pt;">). Visually, this rotation is shown in Fig. </a><span class="s16">4</span><span class="p">.</span></p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">To rotate a shape using this formula, you need to ensure that the center of the shape is the origin (0<span class="s4">, </span>0). It is a part of this assignment to figure out how to rotate a shape that has its center somewhere else.</p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 23pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 83%;text-align: justify;">You should ensure that the following driver method in the <span class="s8">RadialGraph </span>class works with your code (pay attention to the documentation, which explains what must be printed for the test cases used in this driver method, and what exception must be thrown):</p><p class="s13" style="padding-top: 6pt;padding-left: 40pt;text-indent: -16pt;text-align: left;">public static void main(String... args) { Point center = new Point(&quot;center&quot;, 0, 0); Point east = new Point(&quot;east&quot;, 1, 0); Point west = new Point(&quot;west&quot;, -1, 0); Point north = new Point(&quot;north&quot;, 0, 1); Point south = new Point(&quot;south&quot;, 0, -1);</p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 40pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Point toofarsouth = new Point(&quot;south&quot;, 0, -2);</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 40pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">// A single node is a valid radial graph.
